## Kadaneâ€™s Algorithm â€” Steps (COMMENT FORMAT)

```java
// 1. Take two variables:
//    currentSum â†’ sum of current subarray
//    maxSum â†’ maximum subarray sum so far

// 2. Initialize both with first element of array
//    (important to handle all-negative arrays)

// 3. Traverse array from index 1 to end

// 4. For each element, decide:
//    - start new subarray from current element
//    - OR continue previous subarray
//    currentSum = max(arr[i], currentSum + arr[i])

// 5. Update maxSum if currentSum is greater
//    maxSum = max(maxSum, currentSum)

// 6. After loop ends, maxSum is the answer
```

---

## Code with Comments (FINAL)

```java
public static int maxSubArray(int[] arr) {

    // current sum of subarray
    int currentSum = arr[0];

    // maximum sum found so far
    int maxSum = arr[0];

    // traverse from second element
    for (int i = 1; i < arr.length; i++) {

        // choose max: start new OR continue old
        currentSum = Math.max(arr[i], currentSum + arr[i]);

        // update overall maximum
        maxSum = Math.max(maxSum, currentSum);
    }

    // return maximum subarray sum
    return maxSum;
}
```

---

## Time Complexity (TC)

```
O(n)
```

âœ” Single loop
âœ” Each element visited once

---

## Space Complexity (SC)

```
O(1)
```

âœ” No extra array used
âœ” Only two variables

